            "@type": "dctypes:Text",
            "format": "text/html",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.XVII.R6</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Hot summer night</strong></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-a9cb1383-7fff-9c7b-2629-8826b0111481\">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The &ldquo;hot summer Sunday evening&rdquo; connects the opening of this chapter with the closing of the last. At the end of chapter 23, Arthur &ldquo;took particular notice&hellip; as he afterwards had occasion to remember, of the airlessness and closeness of the house&rdquo; (LD 671). In the opening of this chapter, the same hot oppressiveness characterizes the Sparkler house: &ldquo;The residence&hellip; at all times stuffed and close as if it had an incurable cold in its head, was that evening particularly stifling&rdquo; (673). This note and that below (&ldquo;Such a long, long, Day&hellip;&rdquo;) appear to be part of the same temporal layer as the chapter notes for 23 above given their similar ink and size.&nbsp;</p>"
        }
